Trim it, using [trim][1] method of `String` which &quot;*Returns a copy of the string, with leading and trailing whitespace omitted.*&quot;

Note that it *Returns a copy of the string* and doesn&#39;t edit the `String`

    myString.trim()

**Null Strings**

As @rmertins said, this is not &quot;null safe&quot;, meaning if your `String` is `null` it will throw a `NullPointerException` so if your `String` can be `null`, wrap it.

    if (myString != null)
    {
      String newTrimmedString = myString.trim();
    }

Importing an entire library to do this one task like @rmertins said (i.e. [StringUtils][2] from apache commons) is just overkill I&#39;d say.  I would also say it&#39;s bad practice to pass around `null` objects anyhow and `null` `String` objects suggests bad design.

**What is removed**

It&#39;s worth noting that @JohnyTex pointed out that all characters below \u0020 are removed by `trim()` including carriage return and line-feed.



  [1]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#trim%28%29
  [2]: http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-lang/apidocs/org/apache/commons/lang3/StringUtils.html

Check out the [String.trim() method](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#trim())

    String foo = &quot;\n\n  \n\t actual Value\t\n \n &quot;;
    System.out.println(foo.trim()); //prints &quot;actual Value&quot;

About as simple and elegant as it gets. Keep in mind, though, that this will not only trim newline characters, but tabs, spaces, etc. as well.

